description: This large invasive land planarian was about 7” long but are said to possibly reach 20” or more. They are a voracious predator of earthworms and believed to have originated from south east Asia. They produce the potent neurotoxin tetrodotoxin which is believed to paralyze prey such as earthworms which are rather strong compared to the slow almost limp kewense flat worms. I occasionally find these on moist nights along the perimeter of my lawn where earthworms are often found.

Observation and photo by Sharon Mountford, sent to nature@nhm.org.

Identified by its bright yellow throat, this is an "Audubon's" Yellow-rumped Warbler, the common wintering subspecies throughout much of California. What makes this photo particularly interesting (to me) is that you can clearly see how the bird is molting out of its faded blue-gray breeding plumage into its fresh, brownish, stripe-backed winter plumage.

Like tiny, aerial cleaner shrimp, warblers were feeding on the many flies that were congregating around the lounging elephant seals.

Golden-crowned Sparrows (Zonotricha atricapilla) (bird on the left) are common wintering birds throughout much of California where they often gather together with White-crowned Sparrows (Z. leucophrys). Based on this juvenile White-crown's pale lores, yellow bill, brown back, and inland location, it is almost certainly Z. l. pugetensis, the Puget Sound White Crowned Sparrow.

With it's pale lores, yellowish bill, and fairly short primary projection, this adult is one of the two subspecies of "Pacific" White-crowned Sparrow. Resident along the central California Coast is  the Nuttall's White-Crowned Sparrow, while the nearly identical, more northerly breeding Puget Sound White-crowned Sparrow (Z. l. pugetensis) overlaps in distribution in the winter.

Ruby-crowned Kinglets (family Regulidae) are common winter residents throughout much of California (although they breed in the Sierra Nevadas). One of their distinguishing features, which are often surprisingly easy to see, are their "golden slippers". They have very thin legs with orange feet.

This one is in Coyote Brush (Baccharis pilularis)

description: Poor, distant and low-light documentary photo of this rare bird to San Diego County, CA.  Found by Paul Lehman on 10-31-12.

While songs are generally thought to be learned among birds, the calls, which are not believed to be learned, were also like Anna's in this individual despite the overall appearance of a Costa's. The tail of the Costa's typically does not exceed the tip of the primaries this much (and all primaries present - count them). Gorget and crown feathering clearly reddish, and always medium purple in Costa's. Costa's bill is typically curved noticeably downward, while this bird's is nearly straight

Video of this individual that contains the vocalizations can be seen here:
https://www.flickr.com/photos/71649753@N07/8177092038
Note blood-stained beak.  Light levels were somewhat low, which impacted photo quality.

This Fruit Fly was found in a house at 32.829206,-117.168506. I notice that it was very attracted to the scent of apples in the room. I also noticed that the fruit flies would only come out during the night time when there wasn't a lot of people around. So I devised an experiment with apple juice and soap mixed together. The fly was attracted to the sent of apples, and they were caught in the soap. I was able to take a picture of this fly after it died in the soap. This observation is part of the High Tech High Insects of San Diego Field Guide.

description: American Crows are familiar over much of the continent: large, intelligent, all-black birds with hoarse, cawing voices. They are common sights in treetops, fields, and roadsides, and in habitats ranging from open woods and empty beaches to town centers. They usually feed on the ground and eat almost anything – typically earthworms, insects and other small animals, seeds, and fruit but also garbage, carrion, and chicks they rob from nests. Their flight style is unique, a patient, methodical flapping that is rarely broken up with glides. Crows are rarely found alone.

description:
At dusk a mob of scolding jays drew my attention to a large nest in an oak tree at Guadalupe Oak Grove Park in San Jose, Ca. In the fading light I could make out the silhouette of what I first thought was a Great Horned Owl. But this nest didn't look like any Great Horned Owl nest I'd seen; it was the leafy nest of a squirrel. Through binoculars I could see that it was a bobcat in the tree. It is still a little hard to believe a bobcat would fit in this nest. Although it was large for a squirrels nest, it seems like it would be a bit cramped for a bobcat. 

The details I could see through binoculars don't show up in the photo, nor does the photo capture the green-gold of the eyeshine.

description:
This morning on my walk to work I was lucky to watch a small bird of prey catch a rock dove in the air. I saw the motion of the catch  peripherally (fairly close to the ground), then spotted the hunter carrying the dead rock dove up to the corner of a nearby building (around six stories up). The photo shows it before it dragged its meal out of view, and gives a sense of scale (scarcely bigger than the darker shadow of the dead pigeon at its feet), build and coloration.

It struck me as a falcon while watching the hunt. Reading about the size and hunting habits of local falcons, my best guess is a Merlin.

description:
Saw this bird perched on the Blue and Gold Fleet entrance sign on Fisherman's Wharf, right after we had all returned from a work cruise.

Skies were gray, air was chilly, windy, and the bird seemed to be unperturbed by the crowd of inebriated and rowdy passengers passing by below it. 

Unfortunately, being a part of that group, I can't remember the details too well beyond recalling that it just continued to blithely ignore us as we all poured out of the boat...

Observed a salamander last night in the garage at around 8:30PM after frantic mother called me on the phone, thinking that it was a sick baby lizard. 

She shone a flashlight on it, and we observed it as it slowly crawled from the outside driveway pavement, into the garage  door crevice, and finally, into the garage where we were standing. Had no idea what it was and looked it up on the laptop, and discovered that it was not a sickly baby lizard at all, but rather, an Arboreal Salamander (Please feel free to correct me--I'm still an amateur at identification and would love to learn something new).

Front and hind legs were raw pink, and the top of its body, from head to tail, appeared to be a dark black-brown murky color. Skin appeared moist, and along the length of its body, from a birds-eye view, were lines similar to those of a roly-poly or millipede, where it could curl up easily. Its tail also appeared to be flexible and easy to curl.

While I had been looking up what the creature was, my mother of her own accord had coaxed it onto a plant tray lined with an old shirt. She did not want to risk running over it in the garage, so we found an oak tree by the house with plenty of holes and cover, and other trees nearby. The ground was still wet from the recent rain. 

On the tray, it had been quite still. But as soon as I held the tray up next to the oak tree, it quickly became active and crawled up onto the bark--thus, it was there that we released it.

description:
Manzanita, Phantom Spires.

According to anecdotal accounts from different climbers that use this area, it had tree cover until "Fred's Fire" in October 2004. If correct, then this is an interesting look at chaparral species well established here eight years after the fire. California Department of Fish and Game's description suggests conifers normally regain dominance from 10 to 40 years after a disturbance. I noticed a few scattered young conifers growing here, but they obviously are far from dominant now.

Ceanothus, Phantom Spires. Sharp and thorny. Dominant for much of the short hike in, with a manzanita species as close second (although the parking area and start of the trail is  under a mature tree canopy).
